00:07:18.620 --> 00:07:21.630
and what kind of
perspective helped

00:07:21.630 --> 00:07:23.650
him make sense of
everything put together?

00:07:23.650 --> 00:07:26.162
LUCY KALANITHI: Yeah, sure.

00:07:26.162 --> 00:07:27.870
And by the way, going
back to that quote,

00:07:27.870 --> 00:07:30.037
"The good news is I've
already outlived two Brontes.

00:07:30.037 --> 00:07:31.870
The bad news is I haven't
written anything."

00:07:31.870 --> 00:07:34.310
It actually gets at
this really deep thing--

00:07:34.310 --> 00:07:35.940
partly that Paul was funny.

00:07:35.940 --> 00:07:38.040
It's like a funny way, in
a way, to tell your best

00:07:38.040 --> 00:07:38.998
friend you have cancer.

00:07:38.998 --> 00:07:43.640
But it's also getting at
his deep ambition in general

00:07:43.640 --> 00:07:46.640
and the fact of what writing
meant to him because he's

00:07:46.640 --> 00:07:48.410
writing this as a neurosurgeon.

00:07:48.410 --> 00:07:50.840
But the big loss in
his mind immediately

00:07:50.840 --> 00:07:55.540
is his medical career
plus his love for writing.

00:07:55.540 --> 00:08:00.150
So Paul, as a child, as
he said in that video,

00:08:00.150 --> 00:08:02.062
had always thought
he'd be a writer.

00:08:02.062 --> 00:08:05.630
Was a real lover of literature
and thought he would--

00:08:05.630 --> 00:08:08.390
he majored in English
and then went on

00:08:08.390 --> 00:08:11.200
to study history and philosophy
of science and medicine.

00:08:11.200 --> 00:08:13.620
And then surprised himself
by becoming a doctor.

00:08:13.620 --> 00:08:15.750
His dad was a doctor
who worked really hard.

00:08:15.750 --> 00:08:19.140
And initially Paul said, I
don't want to work in that way

00:08:19.140 --> 00:08:21.960
and thought he would
enter the humanities.

00:08:21.960 --> 00:08:26.330
And then ultimately
had this realization

00:08:26.330 --> 00:08:28.010
that meant a lot
to him, which was

00:08:28.010 --> 00:08:31.000
many of the critical,
life-changing moments we all

00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:35.510
face happen in a
medical context.

00:08:35.510 --> 00:08:37.640
And that's good news and
bad news-- everything

00:08:37.640 --> 00:08:40.601
from having a baby to having
a serious illness or trauma.

00:08:43.460 --> 00:08:48.120
He's sort of seeking what are
the underpinnings of meaning

00:08:48.120 --> 00:08:50.880
in our lives, from all
these various ways?

00:08:50.880 --> 00:08:54.260
And I'll just give an example.

00:08:54.260 --> 00:08:56.900
When Paul was becoming
more and more ill

00:08:56.900 --> 00:09:00.360
and having unexplained
symptoms when he was 36,

00:09:00.360 --> 00:09:01.545
he started losing weight.

00:09:01.545 --> 00:09:04.510
He started having terrible back
pain, and then night sweats

00:09:04.510 --> 00:09:07.050
and chest pain and
a cough, and had

00:09:07.050 --> 00:09:09.380
been working with his
doctor to figure out why.

00:09:09.380 --> 00:09:11.125
And then he got a chest x-ray.

00:09:11.125 --> 00:09:13.940
It had nodules on it.

00:09:13.940 --> 00:09:18.280
And maybe it was
tuberculosis and most likely

00:09:18.280 --> 00:09:19.460
it was metastatic cancer.

00:09:19.460 --> 00:09:20.580
And both of us knew that.

00:09:20.580 --> 00:09:23.700
And we were on our way
to Stanford Hospital

00:09:23.700 --> 00:09:27.320
because he was admitted to the
hospital for expedited work

00:09:27.320 --> 00:09:31.370
up of what's causing these
symptoms and the x-ray problem.

00:09:31.370 --> 00:09:33.850
And he packed three
books, actually,

00:09:33.850 --> 00:09:37.600
to take with him
to the hospital.

00:09:37.600 --> 00:09:40.804
And I was packing all the junk
like fuzzy socks and a health

00:09:40.804 --> 00:09:41.970
insurance card and whatever.

00:09:41.970 --> 00:09:44.553
And he's got this stack of books
that he's carrying with them.

00:09:44.553 --> 00:09:48.800
And the books were "Mere
Christianity" by CS Lewis,

00:09:48.800 --> 00:09:52.270
and a novel by
Solzhenitsyn, "Cancer Ward,"

00:09:52.270 --> 00:09:53.680
and "Being in
Time" by Heidegger,

00:09:53.680 --> 00:09:56.020
which I don't know how you
concentrate on that book

00:09:56.020 --> 00:09:58.561
when you're feeling well, let
alone when you're feeling sick.

00:09:58.561 --> 00:10:01.450
But it was this stack of
literature and religion

00:10:01.450 --> 00:10:02.220
and philosophy.

00:10:02.220 --> 00:10:04.120
And they were sort of
like a little amulet.

00:10:04.120 --> 00:10:06.000
Like, I'm not taking
a medical text.

00:10:06.000 --> 00:10:11.250
I'm taking literature and books.

00:10:11.250 --> 00:10:14.827
So I think if you think
about literature or science

00:10:14.827 --> 00:10:17.410
or philosophy, they're all sort
of aiming at this question of,

00:10:17.410 --> 00:10:18.620
who are we as humans?

00:10:18.620 --> 00:10:19.722
What are we doing here?

00:10:19.722 --> 00:10:20.680
What do our lives mean?

00:10:20.680 --> 00:10:23.070
And I think he sort of
understood that all of those

00:10:23.070 --> 00:10:27.010
are paths to answering these
bigger questions that are not

00:10:27.010 --> 00:10:31.580
just technical, but sort of rich
and in many ways unanswerable.

00:10:31.580 --> 00:10:38.980
So I guess maybe that's
what I would say about that.

00:10:38.980 --> 00:10:40.770
And also, I think Paul
had been interested

00:10:40.770 --> 00:10:43.990
in this question
of human suffering

00:10:43.990 --> 00:10:46.250
and wrapping his head around
mortality and suffering.

00:10:46.250 --> 00:10:51.319
So I think when he himself
became ill, being a physician

00:10:51.319 --> 00:10:53.610
and being a reader, he had
a language to talk about it,

00:10:53.610 --> 00:10:54.109
right?

00:10:54.109 --> 00:10:57.140
I mean, reading
deepens our empathy.

00:10:57.140 --> 00:10:59.780
That's part of why we
read is to experience

00:10:59.780 --> 00:11:02.170
lives that are not our own.

00:11:02.170 --> 00:11:03.880
So he was able to
sort of fall back

00:11:03.880 --> 00:11:07.170
on those tools when
he became sick.

00:11:07.170 --> 00:11:10.650
And I think he says this
lovely thing in his writing

00:11:10.650 --> 00:11:13.320
where he says, I
didn't ask, why me?

00:11:13.320 --> 00:11:16.150
The answer to the question would
have been, well, why not me?

00:11:16.150 --> 00:11:19.860
And I think he sort
of had that approach

00:11:19.860 --> 00:11:21.120
to thinking about suffering.

00:11:21.120 --> 00:11:22.870
And it helped him
when he became ill.

00:11:22.870 --> 00:11:25.680
And some of that came
from practicing medicine

00:11:25.680 --> 00:11:27.869
and some came from literature.

00:11:27.869 --> 00:11:29.410
SPEAKER: In fact,
in the book there's

00:11:29.410 --> 00:11:32.000
this passage where he
describes first seeing

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:34.640
